{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:20:18.194540", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic report — network state analysis\n\nSummary (high level)\n- Overall IP-layer connectivity and routing is healthy: OSPF adjacency and route distribution are stable; hosts and servers can ping each other and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24).\n- There is a clear, isolated service outage: DNS (port 53) queries from hosts to the DNS server (10.200.0.2) are timing out — name resolution from hosts fails even though the DNS process is listening.\n- Localization: the problem is localized to the dns_server node (10.200.0.2).\n- Root cause: local packet-filter rules (nftables filter table) on dns_server are dropping DNS traffic (tcp/udp dport 53), preventing queries from being accepted/answered. This is contradicted by the DNS daemon listening on 10.200.0.2:53, so the service itself is up but network traffic to/from it is being dropped locally.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) Control-plane and routing health\n- FRR/OSPF looks healthy and converged across routers. Examples:\n  - router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3, server_access_router all show OSPF routes for 10.1.x.0/24, 10.2.x.0/24 and 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - OSPF neighbor state shows full adjacencies on the core links (show ip ospf neighbor output shows Full/DR and Full/Backup states).\n- Routing tables indicate routes to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) are present and reachable via the expected next-hops.\n\n2) Data-plane reachability (ICMP)\n- Many reachability tests succeeded (ping matrix from hosts and servers):\n  - Example: host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ~3.9 ms.\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ~3.3 ms.\n- These results demonstrate that the network routing and L3 connectivity between hosts and the server farm (including the DNS host) are functioning.\n\n3) DNS process state on dns_server\n- Named/BIND is running and listening on 10.200.0.2:53 (and loopback). Netstat/ss confirms listening sockets:\n  - netstat shows several entries for 10.200.0.2:53 LISTEN.\n  - ss output shows UNCONN entries for 10.200.0.2:53 (UDP) indicating named bound to that address/port.\n- DNS zone file present and contains records (db.local lists ns1 A 10.200.0.2 and web0..web3 and web99 A records).\n\n4) DNS queries from hosts time out\n- Attempts to query the DNS server from a host timed out (dig queries from host_2_1_1_1 to 10.200.0.2 consistently timed out).\n  - Example: dig +time=2 +tries=1 web0.local @10.200.0.2 produced \"communications error ... timed out / no servers could be reached\".\n- On the dns_server itself, tcpdump attempts to capture DNS traffic timed out (tcpdump command attempts did not return in the timed window), but the observable evidence below explains likely why.\n\n5) Local firewall rules on dns_server are dropping DNS traffic\n- nftables ruleset on dns_server contains explicit drop rules for DNS (both UDP and TCP port 53) in the filter table:\n  - Output excerpt: in table inet filter:\n    - chain input ... tcp dport 53 drop\n    - chain input ... udp dport 53 drop\n    - chain forward ... tcp dport 53 drop\n    - chain forward ... udp dport 53 drop\n    - chain output ... tcp dport 53 drop\n    - chain output ... udp dport 53 drop\n- iptables legacy listing shows default ACCEPT but nft shows a filter table actively dropping DNS; the nft rules are the operative packet filter here.\n- Effect: even though named is listening, incoming DNS packets (UDP/TCP dport 53) are being dropped by the host's packet filter before the server can process/respond to them. The output-side drop rules also indicate responses could be blocked.\n\nSynthesis / root-cause identification\n- Anomaly: DNS name resolution from hosts is failing (dig times out), despite L3 connectivity and a running DNS server.\n- Faulty device(s): dns_server (10.200.0.2) — specifically its local packet-filter configuration.\n- Root cause: nftables filter table contains rules that drop TCP/UDP traffic to/from port 53. This prevents DNS queries from reaching the DNS daemon and/or responses from leaving the host. The DNS service itself (named) and the OSPF/routing framework are otherwise healthy.\n\nImpact\n- Hosts cannot resolve names in the local zone (web0.local … web99.local) via the authoritative DNS server; therefore services published by name (e.g., web99.local) are unreachable by name from hosts even though the IP-layer path to web servers and load-balancer is functional.\n- Direct access by IP to web servers or the load-balancer should still work (routing/ICMP confirmed), but name-based service access is impaired.\n\nObserved artifacts (selected)\n- Ping success: host_2_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.3 (web_server_0): 4/4 replies, rtt avg 3.91 ms.\n- Dig from host timing out: \"communications error to 10.200.0.2#53: timed out\" / \"no servers could be reached\".\n- netstat/ss on dns_server: named listening on 10.200.0.2:53.\n- nft rules showing explicit drops for tcp/udp dport 53 in filter table (input/forward/output chains).\n\nNotes / caveats\n- There are Docker-related NAT rules present as well (the system shows DOCKER_* NAT table entries), but the immediate cause of DNS query failure is the explicit drop rules for port 53 in the filter table.\n- tcpdump attempts on the dns_server timed out during capture attempts; however the packet filter evidence is sufficient to explain the behavior.\n\nNo remediation actions are included in this report (per instructions). If you want, I can next produce:\n- A concise list of exactly which rules on dns_server are causing drops (full nft ruleset lines) and timestamps, or\n- A verification plan (commands to run) to confirm DNS packets are dropped/accepted after any change, or\n- If you want mitigation steps, I can produce recommended changes to restore DNS functionality.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 19424, "output_tokens": 2274, "total_tokens": 21698, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 17920}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 832}}}
